The Telegraph - Calcutta : Sports

 Saturday, May 28, 2005 

 New Delhi: India can hope for their maiden Olympic medal in boxing should the efforts of the international boxing association (AIBA) to include the women?s event in the 2008 Beijing Games succeed. India can base their dreams on M.C. Marycom (46kg), the reigning world and Asian champion, after AIBA president Anwar Chowdhry said the IOC has agreed in principle that women?s boxing would be part of the 2008 Games.

 Memphis: Arjun Atwal hit a par opening round at the US PGA Tour?s St Jude Classic here Thursday to be at joint 57th place. Justin Leonard of the US was leading with a nine-under round of 62, followed by Kirk Triplett, Davis Love III, Javon Bohn and Matt Gogel (66).

 Madrid: Real Madrid striker Michael Owen has no regrets over moving to Spain, after watching his former club Liverpool beat AC Milan to win the Champions League final on Wednesday. ?I am delighted that my friends won the Champions League, and I am equally as happy with the decision I took to leave Liverpool,? Owen told a sports daily on Friday.

